  "prompt": "What is the main function of the brachiocephalic artery?",
  "response": "The **brachiocephalic artery**, also known as the **brachiocephalic trunk** or **innominate artery**, is a major blood vessel that arises from the **aortic arch** in humans. Its **main function** is to distribute **oxygenated blood** from the heart to the **right arm** and the **right side of the head and neck**. \n\nIt achieves this by **branching into two primary arteries**:\n\n1. **Right Subclavian Artery**: Supplies blood to the right arm.\n2. **Right Common Carotid Artery**: Supplies blood to the right side of the head and neck, including the brain.\n\nBy serving as the conduit for these critical arteries, the brachiocephalic artery plays a vital role in ensuring that the right side of the upper body receives the necessary oxygen and nutrients to function properly.\n\n**Additional Context:**\n\n- **Location**: The brachiocephalic artery is the first major branch of the aortic arch.\n- **Presence in Humans**: In humans, only the right side has a brachiocephalic trunk. The left common carotid and left subclavian arteries branch directly from the aortic arch.\n- **Clinical Relevance**: Blockages or abnormalities in the brachiocephalic artery can affect blood flow to the right arm and the right side of the brain, potentially leading to serious health issues.\n\nUnderstanding the anatomy and function of the brachiocephalic artery is essential in fields like cardiology, vascular surgery, and emergency medicine, where maintaining proper blood flow is crucial.",
